Clean IEEE TPS–Aligned Version
Abstract
Electricity markets rely on operating reserve procurement and pricing mechanisms to manage uncertainty arising from high penetrations of wind and solar generation. In current market designs, reserve capacity requirements are typically determined using simplified uncertainty models that neglect the strong spatial correlations induced by weather. This paper proposes a differentiable, learning-based robust optimization framework in which the geometry of ellipsoidal uncertainty sets is learned end-to-end from data. This allows correlated forecast errors to be incorporated directly into reserve requirements and security-constrained dispatch decisions while preserving computational tractability, thereby improving reserve allocation efficiency and reducing total system costs.
We show that for standard regional (zonal) reserve market formulations, the robust security-constrained economic dispatch problem admits an exact decomposition, yielding closed-form reserve requirements and enabling solver-free, gradient-based learning of uncertainty set parameters. For network-constrained formulations that explicitly account for transmission limits and locational coupling, we derive an envelope-gradient method that permits efficient backpropagation without differentiating through the market-clearing optimization. To ensure operational reliability and market consistency, the size of the learned uncertainty sets is calibrated using split conformal prediction, providing finite-sample coverage guarantees.
Numerical experiments on the IEEE 118-bus system demonstrate that learning correlated uncertainty sets leads to 15–18% reductions in calibrated operating reserve procurement costs relative to commonly used diagonal and covariance-based benchmarks, while maintaining prescribed reliability levels. The results highlight how differentiable robust optimization can support data-driven market design by improving the efficiency of reserve procurement and the treatment of uncertainty in price formation.

Introduction
Electricity markets rely on operating reserve procurement and pricing mechanisms to manage uncertainty arising from high penetrations of wind and solar generation. Renewable forecast errors are not only sizable but also strongly correlated across locations and time due to common weather patterns. When such correlation is ignored, reserve capacity requirements are often inefficiently allocated across the power network, leading to excessive procurement costs, distorted price signals, and reduced overall market efficiency. From auction design theory, the independence assumption plays a central role—for example, it underlies Myerson’s lemma and revenue equivalence results. Accordingly, understanding and modeling correlated uncertainty is a critical task for both reliable system operation and effective market design.
Robust optimization is a common analytical tool for incorporating uncertainty into power system operations and market clearing, particularly in the determination of reserve requirements. In most practical implementations, however, uncertainty sets are specified with fixed geometric structure (e.g., polyhedral or spherical sets with prescribed covariance), and only their overall size is tuned to meet reliability criteria. While this approach supports tractable market clearing, it limits the ability of reserve and dispatch mechanisms to adapt to spatially and temporally varying correlation patterns observed in renewable forecast errors. This motivates the need for data-driven uncertainty sets that can adapt to observed correlation structures while preserving market tractability.
This paper proposes a learning-based robust optimization framework for operating reserve procurement and economic dispatch in which the geometry of ellipsoidal uncertainty sets is learned directly from data. By expressing uncertainty through ellipsoidal support functions, the proposed approach yields closed-form expressions and gradients that enable integration of robust security-constrained dispatch models into gradient-based learning pipelines. This formulation allows correlated uncertainty to be incorporated into reserve requirements and dispatch decisions without differentiating through the market-clearing problem, preserving scalability and compatibility with existing market formulations.
A key contribution of the paper is the identification of two structurally distinct regimes corresponding to common reserve-market designs. For widely used zonal reserve formulations, in which reserve capacity requirements are determined independently across regions, we show that the robust dispatch problem admits an exact decomposition. In this setting, reserve requirements have closed-form expressions, and the uncertainty set geometry can be learned in a solver-free manner using analytic gradients. For network-constrained formulations that explicitly account for transmission limits and locational coupling through PTDFs, this separability no longer holds. We show, however, that the resulting robust objective remains differentiable via an envelope representation, enabling efficient gradient computation from dual information without backpropagating through the market-clearing solver.
To align learning with operational reliability and market-consistency requirements, we decouple the learning of uncertainty set shape from its size. The ellipsoid geometry is learned from historical data using gradient-based methods, while the uncertainty set radius is calibrated using split conformal prediction to provide finite-sample coverage guarantees. This separation supports reliable operating reserve procurement while avoiding unstable gradient estimates associated with empirical quantiles.
We demonstrate the proposed framework on the IEEE 118-bus system with spatially correlated renewable forecast errors. Numerical results show that learning correlated uncertainty sets reduces calibrated operating reserve procurement costs by 15–18% relative to standard diagonal and covariance-based benchmarks, while maintaining prescribed reliability levels. These results illustrate how differentiable robust optimization can serve as a practical bridge between machine learning and electricity market design, improving both operational efficiency and uncertainty-aware price formation.
To summarize, the paper’s core contribution is a support-function–based robust learning layer that:
Learns ellipsoidal uncertainty sets via a Cholesky factor , capturing correlations directly;
Provides closed-form support values and gradients, enabling efficient backpropagation;
Identifies two distinct training regimes, depending on the structure of uncertainty exposure; and
Uses split conformal calibration to guarantee coverage without contaminating training.
Empirically, the approach reduces calibrated operating reserve costs by 15–18% in realistic power system simulations under correlated uncertainty.

Conclusion
This paper developed a learning-based robust optimization framework for operating reserve procurement and security-constrained economic dispatch that incorporates correlated renewable forecast errors into market-clearing models. By parameterizing uncertainty through ellipsoidal support functions, the proposed approach enables end-to-end learning of uncertainty set geometry with closed-form gradients, avoiding differentiation through optimization solvers. We showed that commonly used zonal reserve market designs admit an exact, solver-free learning regime, while network-constrained formulations remain tractable through an envelope-gradient representation.
Separating the learning of uncertainty set shape from size calibration using conformal prediction provides a practical mechanism for achieving prescribed reliability guarantees while preserving market consistency. Numerical results on the IEEE 118-bus system demonstrate that learning correlated uncertainty sets yields substantial reductions in calibrated operating reserve procurement costs relative to standard benchmarks, without sacrificing reliability.
Overall, the results highlight how differentiable robust optimization can support data-driven reserve-market design by improving the efficiency of reserve procurement and the treatment of uncertainty in price formation. Future work will explore extensions to multi-period and stochastic market clearing, interactions with ramping and frequency reserves, and integration into real-time balancing markets.
